    <name>
      <text>Finding the Hyperbola with Given Focus and Vertices</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<br> Find the hyperbola with focus \( F_{1} ({@focus1_x@}, {@focus1_y@})\) and  \( F_{2} ({@focus2_x@}, {@focus2_y@})\) and vertices \( A_{1}({@ver1_x@}, {@ver1_y@}), A_{2}({@ver2_x@}, {@ver2_y@}) \).
<br>[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3> Worked solution</h3>
<p>To find the hyperbola with focus \( F_{1} ({@focus1_x@}, {@focus1_y@})\) and  \( F_{2} ({@focus2_x@}, {@focus2_y@})\) and vertices \( A_{1}({@ver1_x@}, {@ver1_y@}), A_{2}({@ver2_x@}, {@ver2_y@}) \). we proceed as follows:</p>
<p> The equation of a hyperbola in standard form follows:</p>
 <p>\[  \displaystyle \frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2} - \frac{(y-k)^2}{b^2} = 1\]</p>
<p> Here the center is \((h, k)\) and the vertices are \( (h \pm a, k) \)</p>
<p> In addtion if \(F_{1} (x_{F_{1}}, y_{F_{1}})\) and \(F_{2} (x_{F_{2}}, y_{F_{2}}) \) are the focus, and \( A_{1} (x_{A_{1}}, y_{A_{1}})\), \( A_{2} (x_{A_{2}}, y_{A_{2}})\) are vertices.</p>
<p>let \(F_{1}F_{2}=2\cdot c\) and \(A_{1}A_{2}=2\cdot a\) . Then we have the following relations:</p>
<p>\(
(1) \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
a^2+b^2= c^2\\ 
2 \cdot a= A_{1} A_{2} 
\end{array}\right. \) 
 and \( (2) \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
h=  \displaystyle \frac{x_{F_{1}}+x_{F_{2}}}{2}\\ 
k=  \displaystyle \frac{y_{F_{1}}+y_{F_{2}}}{2}
\end{array}\right. \) </p>
<p> In this case, focus \( F_{1} ({@focus1_x@}, {@focus1_y@})\) and  \( F_{1} ({@focus2_x@}, {@focus2_y@})\) and vertices \( A_{1}({@ver1_x@}, {@ver1_y@}), A_{2}({@ver2_x@}, {@ver2_y@}) \). </p>
<p>Using the information above we have</p>
<p> \(2 \cdot a =|x_{A_{1}}-x_{A_{2}}|=|({@ver1_x@})-({@ver2_x@})|={@aa@} \implies a =  \displaystyle {@val_a@}\).</p>
<p> \(2 \cdot c =|x_{F_{1}}-x_{F_{2}}|=|({@focus1_x@})-({@focus2_x@})|={@cc@} \implies c =  \displaystyle {@c@}\).</p>
<p> \( b=  \displaystyle {@val_b@} \)</p>
<p> Using the system (2), we get 
\( \left\{ \begin{array}{r}
h=  \displaystyle \frac{({@focus1_x@})+({@focus2_x@})}{2} = {@h@} \\ 
k=  \displaystyle \frac{({@focus1_y@})+({@focus2_y@})}{2} = {@k@}
\end{array}\right. \) </p>
<p> Therefore, the equation of the hyperbola is:</p>
<p> \(  \displaystyle \frac{(x-({@h@}))^2}{@val_a^2@} - \frac{(y-({@k@}))^2}{@val_b^2@} = 1\)</p>
<p> \(  \displaystyle {@hyper2@} \)</p>
<p> \( {@ta1@} \)</p>]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
